window.docContents[64].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals":{"contents":"A Dedekind domain is a Noetherian, integrally closed integral domain of Krull dimension at\nmost one — equivalently, in which every nonzero prime ideal is maximal. Such a domain is\ncharacterised by the property that every nonzero ideal factors uniquely as a product of prime\nideals.\n\nThe ring of integers  of any number field  is a Dedekind domain.\n\nmathlib's IsIntegralClosure.isDedekindDomain verifies the three defining properties\n() for the integral closure  of a Dedekind domain  in a\nfinite separable extension  of ; the number-field case is , , . The closure is integrally closed by transitivity\nof integral closures (IsIntegralClosure.isIntegrallyClosed); it is a finite -module,\nhence Noetherian, because the trace form is nondegenerate over the separable extension\n(, IsIntegralClosure.finite); and every nonzero prime of  is\nmaximal because  is integral over the dimension-one domain \n(IsIntegralClosure.isMaximal_of_isMaximal_comap together with the going-up property), so\n is a field.\n\nIn any Dedekind domain  () — in particular in  —\nthe monoid of nonzero ideals is a unique factorisation monoid: every nonzero ideal  factors as a product of prime ideals\n\nwith the  distinct and , uniquely up to the order of the factors.\n\nThis is the ideal-theoretic form of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic\n(): in a Dedekind domain elements need not factor uniquely, but\nideals do. mathlib derives UniqueFactorizationMonoid (Ideal R) from the fact that the\nnonzero ideals of a Dedekind domain are cancellative and the divisibility order is the\nreverse-inclusion order with the descending-chain condition; concretely the result is read off\nfrom Ideal.isPrincipalIdealRing failing but the fractional ideals forming a free abelian\ngroup on the nonzero primes (). Existence of a factorisation\nuses the Noetherian (ascending chain) condition; uniqueness uses cancellation of the invertible\nprime factors, which is exactly the invertibility supplied by the fractional-ideal group.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory","header":"3.2. Dedekind domains and unique factorisation of ideals","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Adic-spaces___-Huber-rings-and-Tate-rings/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Adic-spaces___-Huber-rings-and-Tate-rings":{"contents":"The constructions above — valuations, the -adic numbers, and the DVR structure of\n — are the arithmetic building blocks for Huber's theory of adic spaces, the\ncorrect foundations for -adic geometry and perfectoid spaces. The nodes in the remainder of this\nchapter are informal: they are formalised in the external project\nAdic-Spaces, built against an incompatible Mathlib\nversion, so they carry no (lean := …) reference. Each records the relevant Lean declaration, an\nexact-source permalink (pinned to commit fb55cd8), and its true sorry-status, and connects into the\ngraph through the Mathlib-backed valuation nodes above.\n\nA topological ring  is a Huber ring (or -adic ring) if it admits a pair of definition:\nan open subring  together with a finitely generated ideal  such\nthat the subspace topology on  equals the -adic topology — equivalently, the powers\n form a neighbourhood basis of  in . The ring  is a ring of definition and\n an ideal of definition;  is not unique, but any two ideals of definition of  have\nthe same radical, and the topologically nilpotent elements of  are open. Following Wedhorn §6.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: PairOfDefinition, IsHuberRing — sorry-free.\n\nA Tate ring is a Huber ring () that contains a topologically nilpotent unit:\nan element  with . Such a  is a pseudo-uniformiser, the role of a\nuniformising parameter in non-archimedean geometry. In a Tate ring the set  of\ntopologically nilpotent elements is open (Proposition 6.13(1)), and every -adic field\n () is a Tate ring with pseudo-uniformiser . Following\nWedhorn Definition 6.10.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: IsTateRing, IsTateRing.isOpen_topologicalNilradical — sorry-free.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces","header":"5.10. Adic spaces: Huber rings and Tate rings","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Adic-spaces___-Huber-rings-and-Tate-rings/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Adic-spaces___-Huber-rings-and-Tate-rings"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-valuation-spectrum-and-continuous-valuations/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-valuation-spectrum-and-continuous-valuations":{"contents":"The valuation spectrum  of a commutative ring  is the set of equivalence\nclasses of valuations () on , where  and  are equivalent if\n\nA point is presented as a valuative relation () on . The topology is\ngenerated by the basic open sets\n\nand the support map  is a continuous map\n. Following Wedhorn Definition 4.1.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: ValuationSpectrum, basicOpen, supp — sorry-free.\n\nLet  be a topological ring and  a valuation (). Then\n is continuous if for every  the set  is open in\n. The continuous points of  () form the subspace\n. For a discrete topology every valuation is continuous;\nthe -adic absolute value on  is continuous in this sense. Following Wedhorn\nDefinition 7.7.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: Valuation.IsContinuous, Cont — sorry-free.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces","header":"5.11. The valuation spectrum and continuous valuations","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-valuation-spectrum-and-continuous-valuations/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-valuation-spectrum-and-continuous-valuations"}});